					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Mat=
rix operation which flips a matrix over its diagonal</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article=
 is about the transpose of matrices and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Transpose_of_a_linear_map" title=3D"Transpose of a linear map">linear=
 operators</a>. For other uses, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Transposition_(disambiguation)" class=3D"mw-redirect mw-disambig" title=
=3D"Transposition (disambiguation)">Transposition (disambiguation)</a>.</di=
v>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Matrix_transpose.gif" class=3D"mw-file-descri=
ption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e=
4/Matrix_transpose.gif/210px-Matrix_transpose.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"200" height=3D"257" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"210" d=
ata-file-height=3D"270"></a><figcaption>The transpose <b>A</b><sup>T</sup> =
of a matrix <b>A</b> can be obtained by reflecting the elements along its m=
ain diagonal. Repeating the process on the transposed matrix returns the el=
ements to their original position.</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra" title=3D"Lin=
ear algebra">linear algebra</a>,  the <b>transpose</b> of a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (mathematic=
s)">matrix</a> is an operator that flips a matrix over its diagonal;
that is, transposition switches the row and column indices of the matrix <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span> to produce another matrix, often deno=
ted <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b><sup>T</sup></span> (among other notati=
ons).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Transpose#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>The transpose of a matrix was introduced in 1858 by the British math=
ematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Cayley" title=3D"=
Arthur Cayley">Arthur Cayley</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transpose#cite_note-2"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
=20
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Transpose_of_a_matrix">Tran=
spose of a matrix</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DTranspose&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: T=
ranspose of a matrix"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
This article assumes that matrices are taken over a commutative ring. These=
 results may not hold in the non-commutative case.</div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTranspose&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The transpose of a matrix <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span>, denot=
ed by <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b><sup>T</sup></span>,<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-Whitelaw1991_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Transpose#cite_note-Whitelaw1991-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><sup>T</sup><b>A</b></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b><sup>tr</su=
p></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><sup>t</sup><b>A</b></span> or <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b><sup>t</sup></span>, may be constructed by any of th=
e following methods:
</p>
<ol><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reflection_(mathematics)" =
title=3D"Reflection (mathematics)">Reflect</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A=
</b></span> over its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_diagonal=
" title=3D"Main diagonal">main diagonal</a> (which runs from the top left t=
o the bottom right) to obtain <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b><sup>T</sup><=
/span></li>
<li>Write the rows of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span> as the column=
s of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b><sup>T</sup></span></li>
<li>Write the columns of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span> as the row=
s of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b><sup>T</sup></span></li></ol>
<p>Formally, the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
i</span>th row, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">j=
</span>th column element of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b><sup>T</sup></s=
pan> is the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">j</sp=
an>th row, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">i</spa=
n>th column element of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span>:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \left[\mathbf {A} ^{\text{T}}\right]_{ij}=3D\left[\mathbf {A} \right]_{ji=
}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mrow>
            <mo>[</mo>
            <msup>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">A</mi>
