<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Products">Products</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTranspose&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Products"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span> is an <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><span class=3D"nowrap"><i>m</i> =C3=97 <i>n</i></span></span> matrix and <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b><sup>T</sup></span> is its transpose, then t=
he result of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_multiplication=
" title=3D"Matrix multiplication">matrix multiplication</a> with these two =
matrices gives two square matrices: <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A A</b><sup>=
T</sup></span> is <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"nowrap"><i>m</i> =
=C3=97 <i>m</i></span></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b><sup>T</s=
up> <b>A</b></span> is <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"nowrap"><i>n<=
/i> =C3=97 <i>n</i></span></span>. Furthermore, these products are <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetric_matrices" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Symmetric matrices">symmetric matrices</a>. Indeed, the matrix pr=
oduct <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A A</b><sup>T</sup></span> has entries tha=
t are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inner_product" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Inner product">inner product</a> of a row of <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span> with a column of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b=
>A</b><sup>T</sup></span>. But the columns of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A<=
/b><sup>T</sup></span> are the rows of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></sp=
an>, so the entry corresponds to the inner product of two rows of <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span>. If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i><sub><i>=
ij</i></sub></span> is the entry of the product, it is obtained from rows <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">i</span> and <span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">j</span> in <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span>. The entry <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i><s=
ub><i>ji</i></sub></span> is also obtained from these rows, thus <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i><sub><i>ij</i></sub> =3D <i>p</i><sub><i>ji</i></sub>=
</span>, and the product matrix (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>p</i><sub><i>ij=
</i></sub></span>) is symmetric. Similarly, the product <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><b>A</b><sup>T</sup> <b>A</b></span> is a symmetric matrix.
</p><p>A quick proof of the symmetry of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A A</b><=
sup>T</sup></span> results from the fact that it is its own transpose:
</p>
