<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Implementation_of_matrix_tr=
ansposition_on_computers">Implementation of matrix transposition on compute=
rs</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTranspose=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Implementation o=
f matrix transposition on computers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-place_matrix_transpos=
ition" title=3D"In-place matrix transposition">In-place matrix transpositio=
n</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Row_and_column_major_order.svg" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
/thumb/4/4d/Row_and_column_major_order.svg/250px-Row_and_column_major_order=
.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"253" class=3D"mw-file-=
element" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"683"></a><figcaption>I=
llustration of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Row-_and_column-maj=
or_order" title=3D"Row- and column-major order">row- and column-major order=
</a> </figcaption></figure>
<p>On a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer" title=3D"Compute=
r">computer</a>, one can often avoid explicitly transposing a matrix in <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_access_memory" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Random access memory">memory</a> by simply accessing the sa=
me data in a different order. For example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Software_libraries" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Software librar=
ies">software libraries</a> for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Li=
near_algebra" title=3D"Linear algebra">linear algebra</a>, such as <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BLAS" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"BLAS=
">BLAS</a>, typically provide options to specify that certain matrices are =
to be interpreted in transposed order to avoid the necessity of data moveme=
nt.
</p><p>However, there remain a number of circumstances in which it is neces=
sary or desirable to physically reorder a matrix in memory to its transpose=
d ordering. For example, with a matrix stored in <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Row-_and_column-major_order" title=3D"Row- and column-major =
order">row-major order</a>, the rows of the matrix are contiguous in memory=
 and the columns are discontiguous. If repeated operations need to be perfo=
rmed on the columns, for example in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Fast_Fourier_transform" title=3D"Fast Fourier transform">fast Fourier t=
ransform</a> algorithm, transposing the matrix in memory (to make the colum=
ns contiguous) may improve performance by increasing <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Memory_locality" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Memory l=
ocality">memory locality</a>.
</p><p>Ideally, one might hope to transpose a matrix with minimal additiona=
l storage. This leads to the problem of transposing an <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>n</i> =C3=97 <i>m</i></span> matrix <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/In-place" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"In-place">in-place</a>, w=
ith <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_O_notation" title=3D"Big O=
 notation">O(1)</a> additional storage or at most storage much less than <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>mn</i></span>. For <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i=
> =E2=89=A0 <i>m</i></span>, this involves a complicated <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation" title=3D"Permutation">permutation</a> o=
f the data elements that is non-trivial to implement in-place. Therefore, e=
fficient <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-place_matrix_transposi=
tion" title=3D"In-place matrix transposition">in-place matrix transposition=
</a> has been the subject of numerous research publications in <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=3D"Computer science">c=
omputer science</a>, starting in the late 1950s, and several algorithms hav=
e been developed.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Transposes_of_linear_maps_a=
nd_bilinear_forms">Transposes of linear maps and bilinear forms</h2><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTranspose&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Transposes of linear maps and =
bilinear forms"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transpose_of_a_linear_ma=
p" title=3D"Transpose of a linear map">Transpose of a linear map</a></div>
<p>As the main use of matrices is to represent linear maps between <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite-dimensional_vector_space" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Finite-dimensional vector space">finite-dimensional =
vector spaces</a>, the transpose is an operation on matrices that may be se=
en as the representation of some operation on linear maps.
</p><p>This leads to a much more general definition of the transpose that w=
orks on every linear map, even when linear maps cannot be represented by ma=
trices (such as in the case of infinite dimensional vector spaces). In the =
finite dimensional case, the matrix representing the transpose of a linear =
map is the transpose of the matrix representing the linear map, independent=
ly of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basis_(linear_algebra)" =
title=3D"Basis (linear algebra)">basis</a> choice.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Transpose_of_a_linear_map">=
Transpose of a linear map</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DTranspose&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Transpose of a linear map"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transpose_of_a_linea=
r_map" title=3D"Transpose of a linear map">Transpose of a linear map</a></d=
iv>
<p>Let <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>X</i><sup>#</sup></span> denote the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_dual_space" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Algebraic dual space">algebraic dual space</a> of an <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span>-<a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Module_(mathematics)" title=3D"Module (mathematics=
)">module</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</=
span>.=20
Let <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span> and =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">Y</span> be <span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span>-modules.=20
If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i>&nbsp;: <i>X</i> =E2=86=92 <i>Y</i></spa=
n> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_map" title=3D"Linea=
r map">linear map</a>, then its <b>algebraic adjoint</b> or <b>dual</b>,<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESchaeferWolff1999128_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transpose#cite_note-FOOTNOTESchaeferWo=
lff1999128-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> is the map <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i><sup>#<=
/sup>&nbsp;: <i>Y</i><sup>#</sup> =E2=86=92 <i>X</i><sup>#</sup></span> def=
ined by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i> =E2=86=A6 <i>f</i> =E2=88=98 <i>u<=
/i></span>.=20
The resulting functional <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i><sup>#</sup>(<i>f<=
/i>)</span> is called the <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pullb=
ack_(differential_geometry)" title=3D"Pullback (differential geometry)">pul=
lback</a></b> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
f</span> by <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">u</sp=
an>.=20
The following <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relation_(math)" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Relation (math)">relation</a> characterizes the=
 algebraic adjoint of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">u</span><sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transpose#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=9F=A8<i>u</i><su=
p>#</sup>(<i>f</i>), <i>x</i>=E2=9F=A9</span> =3D <span class=3D"nowrap">=
=E2=9F=A8<i>f</i>, <i>u</i>(<i>x</i>)=E2=9F=A9</span></span> for all <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i> =E2=88=88 <i>Y</i><sup>#</sup></span> and <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=88 <i>X</i></span></dd></dl>
<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=9F=A8=E2=80=A2,=
 =E2=80=A2=E2=9F=A9</span></span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Natural_pairing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Natural pairing">nat=
ural pairing</a> (i.e. defined by <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"no=
wrap">=E2=9F=A8<i>h</i>, <i>z</i>=E2=9F=A9</span>&nbsp;:=3D <i>h</i>(<i>z</=
i>)</span>).=20
This definition also applies unchanged to left modules and to vector spaces=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Transpose#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The definition of the transpose may be seen to be independent of any=
 bilinear form on the modules, unlike the adjoint (<a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Transpose#Adjoint">below</a>).
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_dual_space" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Continuous dual space">continuous dual space=
</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topological_vector_space=
" title=3D"Topological vector space">topological vector space</a> (TVS) <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span> is denoted =
by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>X</i><span style=3D"font-size:120%"><span cla=
ss=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.15em;">=E2=80=B2</span></span></span>=
.=20
If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span> and <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">Y</span> are TVSs =
then a linear map <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i>&nbsp;: <i>X</i> =E2=86=
=92 <i>Y</i></span> is <b>weakly continuous</b> if and only if <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i><sup>#</sup>(<i>Y</i><span style=3D"font-size:120%"><s=
pan class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.15em;">=E2=80=B2</span></span>=
) =E2=8A=86 <i>X</i><span style=3D"font-size:120%"><span class=3D"nowrap" s=
tyle=3D"padding-left:0.15em;">=E2=80=B2</span></span></span>, in which case=
 we let <span class=3D"texhtml"><sup>t</sup><i>u</i>&nbsp;: <i>Y</i><span s=
tyle=3D"font-size:120%"><span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.15em=
;">=E2=80=B2</span></span> =E2=86=92 <i>X</i><span style=3D"font-size:120%"=
><span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.15em;">=E2=80=B2</span></sp=
an></span> denote the restriction of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i><sup>#=
</sup></span> to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>Y</i><span style=3D"font-size:1=
20%"><span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0.15em;">=E2=80=B2</span>=
</span></span>.=20
The map <span class=3D"texhtml"><sup>t</sup><i>u</i></span> is called the <=
b>transpose</b><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTETr=C3=A8ves2006240_8-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transpose#cite_note-FO=
OTNOTETr%C3%A8ves2006240-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">u</span>.=20
</p><p>If the matrix <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span> describes a li=
near map with respect to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basis_(li=
near_algebra)" title=3D"Basis (linear algebra)">bases</a> of <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span> and <span class=3D"tex=
html mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">W</span>, then the matrix <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b><sup>T</sup></span> describes the transpose of that =
linear map with respect to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dua=
l_basis" title=3D"Dual basis">dual bases</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Transpose_of_a_bilinear_for=
m">Transpose of a bilinear form</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DTranspose&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"=
Edit section: Transpose of a bilinear form"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilinear_form" title=
=3D"Bilinear form">Bilinear form</a></div>
<p>Every linear map to the dual space <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i>&nbsp=
;: <i>X</i> =E2=86=92 <i>X</i><sup>#</sup></span> defines a bilinear form <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>B</i>&nbsp;: <i>X</i> =C3=97 <i>X</i> =E2=86=92 <=
i>F</i></span>, with the relation <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>B</i>(<i>x</i>=
, <i>y</i>) =3D <i>u</i>(<i>x</i>)(<i>y</i>)</span>.=20
By defining the transpose of this bilinear form as the bilinear form <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"><sup>t</sup><i>B</i></s=
pan> defined by the transpose <span class=3D"texhtml"><sup>t</sup><i>u</i>&=
nbsp;: <i>X</i><sup>##</sup> =E2=86=92 <i>X</i><sup>#</sup></span> i.e. <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><sup>t</sup><i>B</i>(<i>y</i>, <i>x</i>) =3D <sup>t</s=
up><i>u</i>(=CE=A8(<i>y</i>))(<i>x</i>)</span>, we find that <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>B</i>(<i>x</i>, <i>y</i>) =3D <sup>t</sup><i>B</i>(<i>y</i>, <=
i>x</i>)</span>.=20
Here, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=A8</spa=
n> is the natural <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homomorphism" ti=
tle=3D"Homomorphism">homomorphism</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>X</i> =E2=
=86=92 <i>X</i><sup>##</sup></span> into the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Double_dual" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Double dual">double =
dual</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Adjoint">Adjoint</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTranspose&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Adjoint"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Not to be confused with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermitian_=
adjoint" title=3D"Hermitian adjoint">Hermitian adjoint</a>.</div>
<p>If the vector spaces <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">X</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">Y</span> have respectively <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nond=
egenerate_form" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Nondegenerate form">nondegen=
erate</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilinear_form" title=3D"=
Bilinear form">bilinear forms</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>B</i><sub><i>X=
</i></sub></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>B</i><sub><i>Y</i></sub></=
span>, a concept known as the <b>adjoint</b>, which is closely related to t=
he transpose, may be defined:
</p><p>If <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i>&nbsp;: <i=
>X</i> =E2=86=92 <i>Y</i></span></span> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Linear_map" title=3D"Linear map">linear map</a> between <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_space" title=3D"Vector space">vect=
or spaces</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</=
span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">Y</span=
>, we define <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">g</s=
pan> as the <b>adjoint</b> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">u</span> if <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
g</i>&nbsp;: <i>Y</i> =E2=86=92 <i>X</i></span></span> satisfies
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e B_{X}{\big (}x,g(y){\big )}=3DB_{Y}{\big (}u(x),y{\big )}}">
  <semantics>
