</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/d9e1f7d7b26922fab10c0b2d9358d686bd013674" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.005ex; width:27.107ex; height:3.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle B_=
{X}{\big (}x,g(y){\big )}=3DB_{Y}{\big (}u(x),y{\big )}}"></span> for all <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=88 <i>X</i></span> and <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i> =E2=88=88 <i>Y</i></span>.</dd></dl>
<p>These bilinear forms define an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Isomorphism" title=3D"Isomorphism">isomorphism</a> between <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span> and <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>X</i><sup>#</sup></span>, and between <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;"><i>Y</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
Y</i><sup>#</sup></span>, resulting in an isomorphism between the transpose=
 and adjoint of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">u=
</span>.=20
The matrix of the adjoint of a map is the transposed matrix only if the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basis_(linear_algebra)" title=3D"Basi=
s (linear algebra)">bases</a> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Orthonormality" title=3D"Orthonormality">orthonormal</a> with respect to th=
eir bilinear forms.=20
In this context, many authors however, use the term transpose to refer to t=
he adjoint as defined here.
</p><p>The adjoint allows us to consider whether <span class=3D"nowrap"><sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i>&nbsp;: <i>Y</i> =E2=86=92 <i>X</i></span></sp=
an> is equal to <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>u</i><sup=
>=E2=80=89=E2=88=921</sup>&nbsp;: <i>Y</i> =E2=86=92 <i>X</i></span></span>=
.=20
In particular, this allows the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ort=
hogonal_group" title=3D"Orthogonal group">orthogonal group</a> over a vecto=
r space <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">X</span> =
with a quadratic form to be defined without reference to matrices (nor the =
components thereof) as the set of all linear maps <span class=3D"nowrap"><s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>X</i> =E2=86=92 <i>X</i></span></span> for which t=
he adjoint equals the inverse.
</p><p>Over a complex vector space, one often works with <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sesquilinear_form" title=3D"Sesquilinear form">sesqu=
ilinear forms</a> (conjugate-linear in one argument) instead of bilinear fo=
rms.=20
The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermitian_adjoint" title=3D"He=
rmitian adjoint">Hermitian adjoint</a> of a map between such spaces is defi=
ned similarly, and the matrix of the Hermitian adjoint is given by the conj=
ugate transpose matrix if the bases are orthonormal.
</p>
